Visualizing the Winter Olympics

Nathan Colbert

Introduction

In the spirit of the most exciting sporting event, I thought it would be interesting to create some visualizations centered around Winter Olympics of days gone by. In order to do this I found a couple of data sets that provide the necessary information. The first, ‘winter,’ contains information about the year, city, sport, athelete, and more. This can be seen below.

winter <- read.csv("~/Desktop/Desktop/winter.csv")
options(DT.options = list(pageLength = 3, scrollX = TRUE, scrollY = "165px"))
datatable(winter)

The second, ‘dictionary,’ contains information about countries and their country code, populations, and GDP. This can be seen below.

dictionary <- read.csv("~/Desktop/Desktop/dictionary.csv")
datatable(dictionary)

Some recoding

In order to get the most use out of these data sets, I first had to recode some of the variables. For example, in order to join the two datasets I have to make sure that all of the country codes correspond to one another. In the winter dataset, there are several different country codes for the same country (Germany has GDR, EAU, FRG, and GER!).

After these adjustments, I was able to join the two datasets to create ‘olympics,’ seen below.

Winter <- rename(winter, Code = Country)
Winter$Code[Winter$Code == "GDR"] <- "GER"
Winter$Code[Winter$Code == "EAU"] <- "GER"
Winter$Code[Winter$Code == "FRG"] <- "GER" 
Winter$Code[Winter$Code == "URS"] <- "RUS"
Winter$Code[Winter$Code == "EUN"] <- "RUS"
Winter$Code[Winter$Code == "RU1"] <- "RUS"

olympics <- full_join(Winter, dictionary)
datatable(olympics)

Medal Count Over Time

A simple and obvious place to start with this visual analysis of the Winter Olympics is to look at medal count over time. In order to do this, we must create a new dataframe where we each country is represented along with the count of their respective medals won. After this I was able to generate the two graphs seen below.

gold_medal <- olympics %>% select(Country, Medal, Year) %>% 
  filter(Medal == "Gold") %>% 
  group_by(Country) %>% count(Medal)

silver_medal <- olympics %>% select(Country, Medal, Year) %>%
  filter(Medal == "Silver") %>%
  group_by(Country) %>% count(Medal)

bronze_medal <- olympics %>% select(Country, Medal, Year) %>%
  filter(Medal == "Bronze") %>% 
  group_by(Country) %>% count(Medal)

by_country_medal <- full_join(gold_medal, silver_medal,
                              by = "Country")

by_country_medal <- full_join(by_country_medal, bronze_medal,
                              by = "Country")


by_country_medal <- by_country_medal %>% 
  rename("Bronze" = n) %>% rename("Silver" = n.y) %>% 
  rename("Gold" = n.x)  %>% 
  replace_na(list(Gold = 0, Silver = 0, Bronze = 0)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(Gold)) %>% head(n = 10)

test <- by_country_medal %>%  melt() %>% 
  select(Country, variable, value) %>% arrange(Country)


ggplot(test, aes(x = Country, y = value, fill = variable, name = "Medal Type")) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") + 
  ylab("Medals Won") + xlab(NULL) + 
  scale_fill_manual("variable", values = c("Gold"= "tan", 
                                           "Silver" = "light grey", 
                                           "Bronze" = "#A57164")) +
  theme_tufte() + coord_flip() + 
  theme(legend.title = element_blank(),
        plot.title = element_text(size = 18, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5)) +
  labs(title = "Top Ten Most Successful Countries in the Winter Olympics") 

gold_medal_2 <- olympics %>% select(Country, Medal, Year) %>% 
  filter(Medal == "Gold") %>% 
  group_by(Country, Year) %>% count(Medal)

silver_medal_2 <- olympics %>% select(Country, Medal, Year) %>% 
  filter(Medal == "Silver") %>% 
  group_by(Country, Year) %>% count(Medal)

bronze_medal_2 <- olympics %>% select(Country, Medal, Year) %>% 
  filter(Medal == "Bronze") %>% 
  group_by(Country, Year) %>% count(Medal)

by_country_year <- full_join(gold_medal_2, silver_medal_2, 
                             by = c("Country", "Year"))

by_country_year <- full_join(by_country_year, bronze_medal_2, 
                             by = c("Country", "Year"))

by_country_year <- by_country_year %>% rename("Bronze" = n) %>% 
  rename("Silver" = n.y) %>% rename("Gold" = n.x)  %>% 
  replace_na(list(Gold = 0, Silver = 0, Bronze = 0, 
                  Medal.x = "Gold", Medal.y = "Silver", 
                  Medal = "Bronze")) %>% 
  arrange(desc(Gold))


top_ten <- c("United States", "Switzerland", 
             "Sweden", "Russia", "Norway", 
             "Italy", "Germany", "Finland", 
             "Canada", "Austria")

test2 <- by_country_year %>% 
  melt(id.vars = c("Year", "Country"),
       measure.vars = c("Gold", "Silver", "Bronze")) %>%
  filter(Country %in% top_ten) %>% arrange(Year)


medal_time <- ggplot(test2, aes(x = Year, y = value)) + 
  geom_point(aes(group = Country)) + ylab("Total Medals Won") +
  xlab(NULL) + theme_tufte() + geom_line(aes(color = Country))+ 
  facet_wrap(~ Country, nrow = 2) + 
  theme(legend.title = element_blank(),
        plot.title = element_text(size = 18, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5)) + 
  labs(title = "Medals Won by Top Ten Countries Over Time")

medal_time

The contrast between these two graphs provide a great example for the principles of delivering insights with visualization. The line graph is clearly more visually compelling; however, it is much more difficult to discern any really relationships through this graph. The bar chart, on the other hand, although very simple, very quickly and easily delivers a lot of information about medal count over time.

Medal Counts Adjusted by Population and GDP

Seeing medal count alone is interesting enough, but what about accounting for Population and GDP? To look at this, I created two new data frames where the results are scaled by population and GDP. I then generated two bar charts showing the scaled amount of gold medals won of the top ten countries.

by_pop <- olympics %>% select(Country, Medal, Population, GDP.per.Capita) %>% 
  filter(Medal == "Gold") %>% group_by(Country, Population, GDP.per.Capita) %>% 
  count(Medal) %>% 
  mutate(Pop_Scale = n / Population, GDP_scale = n / GDP.per.Capita) %>% 
  arrange(desc(Pop_Scale)) %>% head(n = 10)

ggplot(by_pop, aes(x = reorder(Country, Pop_Scale), y = Pop_Scale * 100000)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "tan") + 
  coord_flip() + xlab(NULL) + ylab("Gold Medal Count Scaled by Population") + 
  theme_tufte() + 
  theme(legend.title = element_blank(), 
        plot.title = element_text(size = 18, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5)) + 
  labs(title = "Top Ten Most Successful Countries Scaled by Population")

by_GDP <- olympics %>% select(Country, Medal, Population, GDP.per.Capita) %>% 
  filter(Medal == "Gold") %>% group_by(Country, Population, GDP.per.Capita) %>% 
  count(Medal) %>% 
  mutate(Pop_Scale = n / Population, GDP_scale = n / GDP.per.Capita) %>% 
  arrange((GDP_scale)) %>% head(n = 10)
 
ggplot(by_GDP, aes(x = reorder(Country, GDP_scale), y = GDP_scale * 10000)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "tan") + coord_flip() + xlab(NULL) + 
  ylab("Gold Medal Count Scaled by GDP") + theme_tufte() + 
  theme(legend.title = element_blank(), 
        plot.title = element_text(size = 18, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5)) + 
  labs(title = "Top Ten Most Successful Countries Scaled by GDP")

Host Country Advantage?

Next, I thought it would be interesting to examine whether or not a host country advantage exists. In order to do this, I needed data on the different host countries. I scraped this data from wikipedia, cleaned it, reduced to the years I already have withing my dataset, and then used it to highlight the years in which a country hosted the olympics.

Country Success by Sport

Another interesting insight that can be gathered from this data is to examine a countries success in the diffirent events in a given sport. For this ecxample, I’m going to examine the sucess of the United States in Skiiing, faceted by gender.

us_ski <- olympics %>% filter(Country == 'United States' & Sport == 'Skiing') 

ggplot(us_ski, aes(x = Event, y = Medal, fill = Medal)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") + facet_grid( ~ Gender) + 
  scale_fill_manual("Medal", values = c("Gold"= "tan", 
                                        "Silver" = "light grey",
                                        "Bronze" = "#A57164")) + 
  coord_flip() + theme_tufte() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(), 
        axis.ticks.x = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "none", 
        plot.title = element_text(size = 18, hjust = .5, face = "bold")) + 
  xlab(NULL) + ylab(NULL) +labs(title = "United States Sucess in Skiing")

Most Successful Atheletes of All Time

m_athletes <- olympics %>% select(Athlete, Medal, Country, Sport, Gender) %>% 
  group_by(Athlete, Country, Sport, Gender) %>% 
  filter(Medal == "Gold") %>% filter(Gender == "Men") %>% count(Medal) %>%  
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% head(n = 25)


ggplot(m_athletes, aes(x = reorder(Athlete, n), y = n, color = Country)) + 
  geom_point(shape = 21, size = 5, stroke = 1)  + 
  theme_tufte() + ylab("Gold Medals Won") + 
  xlab(NULL) + coord_flip()  + 
  labs(title = "Most Successful Male Atheletes of All Time") + 
  theme( plot.title = element_text(size = 18, hjust = .5, face = "bold")) +
  scale_shape(solid = F)

f_athletes <- olympics %>% select(Athlete, Medal, Country, Sport, Gender) %>% 
  group_by(Athlete, Country, Sport, Gender) %>% 
  filter(Medal == "Gold") %>% filter(Gender == "Women") %>% count(Medal) %>%  
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% head(n = 25)

ggplot(f_athletes, aes(x = reorder(Athlete, n), y = n, color = Country)) + 
  geom_point(shape = 21, size = 5, stroke = 1)  + 
  theme_tufte() + ylab("Gold Medals Won") + 
  xlab(NULL) + coord_flip()  + 
  labs(title = "Most Successful Female Atheletes of All Time") + 
  theme( plot.title = element_text(size = 18, hjust = .5, face = "bold")) +
  scale_shape(solid = F)
